<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="7314338991b0242194ea5e63854752a3" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Warg Riders: Playing with the Big Dogs!<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.50)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955'>Kyle "Master Kyle" McEachron</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 21, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <br />
Ok, first I’d like to mention that I started writing this article around the time when the starter deck list was revealed on Decipher, so if some of the card reviews here seem outdated, they are. Second, yes this will review all the cards because I decided to wait to finishimmer until all the cards are revealed. Last, I’d like to say, please don’t dismiss this just because you’ve read other articles on the same topic. I know it’s long, but please don’t murder it before you’ve read it first.<br />
<br />
	In my last article, I reviewed how the southrons get some much needed help from the BOHD cards and maybe, gasp, people will finally use southrons (other than just the Desert Lord) in their deck.<br />
<br />
	This time, though, I’m going into a completely (well… not completely) new culture, the Warg-Riders. The Warg-Riders are not a completely new culture, as the Isengard orcs were released in realms. With every expansion, decipher manages to come up with some new deck concept and that’s what I love so much about this game. The more deck types that are used, the more interesting the play field becomes.<br />
<br />
Like their forging brothers, the Warg-Riders are strongly vitality related. Unlike the original Isenorcs, theses guys make use of their vitality in skirmishes rather than in the regroup. <br />
<br />
First, let’s look at the Warg-riders by themselves. Right off the bat, I could tell that these guys were great for swarming. As far as I can see, these guys get better stats than any other minions with a site number of 4. Take the typical Warg-Rider, for instance. He’s 1 twilight and has a strength of 5 and a vitality of 2. The only other culture, I believe, that has minions who play for 1 and have 2 vitality is Sauron and their minions stop roaming at 6. You’ll also notice that he can become fierce if he’s not exhausted. Ok, admittedly that’s not likely to happen since he’s a 5, but if you got several minions down with him, your opponent may end up assigning him to a weaker companion, thus allowing him to come back for a second skirmish. This might not matter that much, but if all or many the minions you played were warg-riders and stayed healthy, then you could potentially deal some serious damage. <br />
<br />
However, decipher did not create these guys to swarm. Most of them are average strength and cheap. Their Wargs, however, are not. For a possession, they are quite expensive. However, they really beef up your guys, giving them not only very high strength bonuses, but vitality bonuses as well. The typical Warg costs 3 and adds +3 strength and +1 vitality. The bigger version, the War-Warg gives its bearer +4 strength and +2 vitality for 4 twilight. Both, however, have the ability to exert its bearer to cancel a skirmish special ability….as well as Sharku’s Warg giving +5 strength and +3 vitality at a cost of 5. True, it reduces the Warg-rider’s vitality, but if your strength 10 or 12 rider is about to be stealthed away by one of those dumb hobbits, than you’ve at least you’re getting the better end of the bargain. Yes, having stealth prevention can be a powerful thing. I always hate it when a perfectly planned assault at, say, the deep of helm is thwarted by a Swiftly and Softly or 2 and a Filbert Bolger. Yep, those Wargs keep your riders Filbert free. It can prevent Trust Me, Help in Doubt, Servant, Escape, Bounder, and PATHs, not to mention any skirmish event or other ability of any companion. Basically, it guarantees that you will win any skirmish, unless that companion is naturally higher than your minion…which means that once you get down the big suckers, they’re going to have some problems to deal with, all the more likely they will stick around for the fierce.<br />
<br />
Basically, there are 7 Warg-riders in BOHD. The weakest, the Warg-rider is strength 5, 8 with a Warg, 9 with a War-Warg. With a normal Warg, he can take 1 wound and remain fierce, 2 with a War-Warg. This for 4-5 twilight. <br />
<br />
For 1 additional twilight and an extra vitality comes the Isengard Scout Troop. Not efficient at all, stat-wise, but he comes with a nice text similar to Wulf’s. Basically, you can take control of a site for each skirmish you win with an Isey Orc. The thing that makes it better is that it can apply to him as well. Mount him and arm with a Scimitar or Axe so he can win. He’s also fierce, so that’s a potential 2 sites right there. Let’s say you put a Warg on him and an Axe. That’s a net cost of 4 (the Axe adds 1), so you can still play at least another mounted rider and the Rider. The Scout troop is 10 so he’s likely to survive to exert. Mounted or unmounted Orcs can get this bonus, so I play an Orc Overseer to get in a word or two. He costs 5 and has 10, so he’s likely to win. He does, so that’s another site. So for 9 twilight, you take 3 sites. Not bad. Best used with the Riders, though cuz they are fierce. Why does it help to control sites with Isey Orcs? I’ll get to that later.<br />
<br />
The next is the Warg-master is strength 6, 9 with a Warg, 10 with a War-warg. He costs 2 twilight, but allows you to cycle back any warg when you play him. These guys are key to any warg related deck as he allows more flexability with the Wargs. For example, with 4 Warg-masters in your deck, you may not have to put in as many wargs, thus you will have less drawing problems with them. No one wants to get a hand full of wargs without any riders, right? Of course, you’ll have to get your first one before you can get them back. Being the goblin scavengers of this subculture, the Warg-master will also allow you to discard copies of the wargs without having to worry about it. In fact, if you are not getting a lot of minion or twilight, they are the choice cards to discard. You could get away with 2 of each warg, maybe 3. It really depends on how well you cycle cards with your fellowship. Using Elven swords or rare Eowyn can be a way of getting through your deck faster and increasing chances of getting them. Also, I think it is definitely worth mentioning that it is significant that you can choose which warg you pull. You can grab whatever warg best suits your position. A little low on available twilight? Maybe one of those regular Wargs will do the job. Did your opponent just play a companion or two , loaded their fellowship with weapons and flooded the twilight pool? Bring in the heavy artillery War-Wargs and maybe Sharku’s Warg, who plays on any Warg-rider, but you’ll especially want if Sharku is down.<br />
<br />
The Isengard Flanker is next up in the increasing strength line. He’s got a 7 strength, 10 with a Warg, 11 with a War-Warg. He costs 2 twilight as well, but provides nothing other than he is fierce when not exhausted. Still, a potentially fierce minion with 7 strength and stops roaming at 4 for 2 twilight isn’t a bad deal. <br />
<br />
Next we have Sharku himself. I know it is a bit disappointing that the big unique Warg-Rider is only a 7 strength, but it’s probably for the best. Like every other rider, he fierce when not exhausted and he has a very nice ability; he makes the free peoples player exert a non-hobbit companion. This is where the warg-riders start to resemble the former Isen Orcs, which specialized in dealing wounds outside skirmishes. This is certainly a useful text as it forces them to find a place for a wound on a somewhat important companion. No pinning a zillion exertions on Frodo or those unbound hobbits. So with his warg, this guy is strength 12, vitality 5 (which means he will almost always be fierce), damage +1, and gives the freeps a semi-aimed exertion. Not bad for 7 twilight. Him alone is likely to stop a double move because leaving him there means any additional wargs will cost them more exertions and Sharku is already pretty powerful. <br />
     <br />
Next is the Isengard Rider. He plays for 1 more than the Flanker, but he’s got a strength and vitality extra. That makes him 8, 11 with a Warg, 12 with the bigger dog. If you get him down with Sharku’s Warg, he’s got 6 vitality. This may seem to be overkill, but wait till I get to Wolves. <br />
<br />
The most powerful of the riders is the Foul Horde. He’s got a 9, which goes up from there with the addition of a warg. He’s also got 3 vitality and is fierce when not exhausted, gets an ambush of 1 (which can allows you to play events like Wolf Voices), while it has 3 vitality, and gets damage +1 bonus when it has 4. He costs 4 so, while Warg pairing him may not be the most efficient thing (it will cost you a minimum of 7 twilight to mount him), it can still be effective. He is unable to be damage +1 by itself, though, so it is advisable. If they play Rohan, pack at least a War-Warg on him as the Horses exert them. <br />
<br />
That’s all the Riders. Now for the rest.  Saruman, Master of Foul Folk. Let’s start with the bad. He costs 4 and does not fight, meaning that it’s difficult to use him with the riders and expensive mounts. The good. He has the potential to pay it off, literally, he can pay his own costs. Even 3 Axes will nearly pay for him. So you pay 1 for 3 possessions. Not only that, but he heals every one of those orcs twice when the fellowship moves. If I didn’t know any better, I’d say that’s stopping power. Now think of the potential with the Scimitars who add a twilight for each site you control…and there’s no limit! Think about it. With 3 of these in your discard, 3 Orc out, and those same 3 sites from before, you just added 9 twilight. If you had the same scenario as above, but with the max 7 sites under your control (unlikely, but not impossible), then you can add 21 twilight! Sheesh. Who says twilight’s a prob?  If you have plenty, you can always grab a warg. <br />
<br />
As I mentioned, provided you can get a few sites under your belt, Saruman definitely pays off in with Isengard Scimitars (and even Isengard Axes) in the long run. <br />
<br />
What about the events. There’s only one. Wolf Voices. It’s a pump that may seem rather weak, but you have to think about its use. I’ll give you a hint. Think mounts. You want vitality on your Orcs and Rohan nearly always uses mounts, so use this event to pump your guy and heal off the wound, thus also denying your opponent strength advantages with Eomer, Elite Rider, etc… Think back to the Foul Horde….hmmm. That ambush of 1 makes it useful for something. It lets you play this event after twilight is used. This surprise event can throw your opponent off guard as they won’t likely be expecting it unless they stung your hand.<br />
<br />
That leads to the final card, the condition, Wolves of Isengard. Ironically, its game text, despite its title, does not do anything with the wargs. Instead it gives all the Isengard Orcs the regroup ability of the Isengard Retainer, Servant, etc…This is where the riders will start to resemble their brothers, the realms Orcs. Although, this card does not key off of wargs, it is definitely to your benefit to use them as they provide more vitality which will ultimately lead to more wounds. This is another great combo to have Saruman for as you can exert them all the way down, then heal 2 wounds off each if the fellowship moves twice. This could become very powerful. It requires a plains site under your control to play, though, so you’ll want to use a plains site 1 and 2 so whether you go first or second you will be able to take it fast. Also, don’t forget those Scout Troops as you need them to take the sites.<br />
<br />
Well, that about does it for the vicious dogs. One last warning: Beware Possession Removal! That’s all. Hope it was helpful.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
